# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bog-snorkelling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The **Abbots Bromley Horn Dance** is a folk dance which takes place each September in the village of Abbots Bromley in Staffordshire, England.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It is performed by ten dancers, accompanied by a musician playing an accordion and a youth with a triangle.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Six of the dancers carry reindeer horns; the remaining four take the roles of a hobby horse, Maid Marian, a fool, and a youth with a bow and arrow.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] On Wakes Monday the performers dance around the parish all day, beginning early in the morning at the parish church where the horns are stored.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The earliest written record of a hobby-horse performance at Abbots Bromley dates to 1532, and the first mention of the reindeer horns is from 1686.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Radiocarbon dating has shown that at least one of the horns dates to the eleventh century, though it is unknown how or when they came to Staffordshire or became associated with the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Many explanations of the meaning of the dance have been proposed, and it is commonly interpreted as a pagan ritual, but there is no evidence for any of them.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Since Cecil Sharp published the dance in *The Sword Dances of Northern England*, it has been performed outside Abbots Bromley both by the Abbots Bromley dancers themselves and members of the English Folk Dance and Song Society.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It has been depicted in both visual and performance art, and featured in exhibitions about British folk traditions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The earliest written mention of the Abbots Bromley Horn Dance is in Robert Plot's *Natural History of Staffordshire*, published in 1686.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Plot does not seem to have seen the dance himself, but gives a detailed description of the custom.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] According to an annotation by Sir Simon Degge in his copy of Plot's book, he had seen the dance being performed before the English Civil War (1642–1651).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] An earlier mention of the hobby horse at Abbots Bromley from 1532 describes it as an ancient custom, but does not mention the horns.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1976, one of the reindeer horns was radiocarbon dated to 1065 ± 80 years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It is unknown when the horns were brought to Abbots Bromley and when they began to be used in the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Though many sources claim that the dance was first performed at the St Bartholomew's Day fair in 1226, there is no evidence for this supposition.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Many explanations for the origin of the dance have been proposed, though there is no concrete evidence for any of them.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Cawte, it "differs in so many ways from the other ritual dances in this country that it is difficult to understand how it developed its present form".
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It has often been interpreted as the remnant of a pagan ritual.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Violet Alford believed that the dance was originally a winter solstice fertility rite.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Alternatively it has been suggested that it originally was connected to hunting, either as a ritual to encourage or celebrate a successful hunt, or to celebrate the villagers' hunting rights.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the seventeenth century, the dance was performed in the Christmas period – according to Robert Plot, "on New Year, and Twelfth-day" – but it now takes place on the Monday following the first Sunday after September 4.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Plot reports that the dancers collected money for church repairs and to support the parish poor.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the Tudor period, the use of hobby horses to raise money for the parish at Christmas time seems to have been widespread in the north Midlands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Along with Abbots Bromley, it is attested at Stafford and at Culworth in Northamptonshire; a hobby-horse performance at Holme Pierrepont in Nottinghamshire also probably took place in the winter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The horn dance apparently stopped being performed around the time of the English Civil War, before being re-established in the eighteenth century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The Staffordshire antiquarian Richard Wilkes described the dance in his history of the county, suggesting that the tradition had been re-established; his information probably came from around 1725, when he married a woman from Abbots Bromley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] By the late-19th century, the date of the dance had moved to September; Ronald Hutton argues that this change of date probably happened at the time of the re-establishment of the tradition.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Unlike many similar customs, which died out and were revived in the twentieth century, the horn dance has been practiced continuously since the eighteenth century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] According to local tradition, the dance has been led by the same family throughout this period.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The Horn Dance takes place on Wakes Monday, the day following the first Sunday after 4 September.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It previously took place at the beginning of January, on New Year and Twelfth Night.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The dance starts at 8 a.m. at St Nicholas's Church in Abbots Bromley and travels around the parish before returning to the village at the end of the day.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The first dance is outside the vicarage; the dancers subsequently perform in the marketplace and various houses and farms around the parish.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] About midday they dance at Blithfield Hall and have lunch there.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Afterwards, the dancers return to the village, with the final dance around 8 p.m.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the Victorian period, the dancers went out for several days, visiting nearby towns and villages such as Colton and Rugeley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Twelve people perform in the dance: six dancers carrying reindeer horns, a fool, Maid Marian (played by a man wearing women's clothes), a hobby horse, a child with a bow and arrow, a musician, and a child with a triangle.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Of these, the two musicians do not dance; their role is only to accompany the dancers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The dancers use the hobby horse's jaw and the bow and arrow as percussion instruments to keep time with the music.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The Maid Marian carries a ladle used to collect money; the fool has a bladder on a stick.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Plot's account of the dance suggests there may have been only eight or nine performers in his day.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] He does not mention either the fool or the Maid Marian.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The triangle player is a relatively recent addition to the side, only having been introduced at the beginning of the twentieth century; the remainder of the team seems not to have changed significantly at least since the beginning of the nineteenth century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] According to Plot's account, in his day the dancer with the hobby horse also held the bow and arrow; Violet Alford doubts that it was possible for one person to do both.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Wilkes mentions a sword in his description of the dance; though no other source records a sword at Abbots Bromley other morris teams included a sword in their regalia in the nineteenth century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Until the 1880s, dancers wore their ordinary clothes decorated with ribbons.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The original costumes for the horn-carriers were green tunics and blue trousers, both with brown spots or flowers; the dancers now wear either green or red jackets, with green breeches with an oak leaf pattern.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the 1880s the fool wore a furry cap; the 1904 version of the costume introduced jester's motley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The hobby horse is of the tourney style, in which a horse's head and tail are fixed to the performer's body by a frame, which is then covered by a cloth, giving the appearance of a person riding a horse.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Plot's description of the horse, as being made of thin boards carried between the dancer's legs, is more like a stick horse; he does not seem to have actually seen the performance and this is probably an error.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The antlers used in the dance are from reindeer, and date to the 11th century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] As there were no reindeer in Britain at this point, they must have been imported, most likely from Scandinavia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The largest measures 101 cm (40 in) across and weighs 25.5 lb (11.6 kg); the smallest measures 77 cm (30 in) across and the lightest weighs 16.25 lb (7.37 kg).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Three of the sets of antlers are painted white with brown tips and three are painted brown with gold tips; historically the brown antlers have instead been painted blue and red at different times.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the 17th century they had the coats of arms of important local families painted on them, but these are no longer visible.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The antlers are set into wooden heads, thought to date from the 16th century, which are mounted on wooden poles.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The heads are painted brown with features drawn on in red and black.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Historical accounts of the Abbots Bromley dance are inconsistent in their descriptions of the horns.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Plot says that the horns were from reindeer; Wilkes says that they were elk.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Wilkes says that they weighed 56 lb (25 kg); Cecil Sharp says that the heaviest was 90 lb (41 kg).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Wilkes claimed that the horns were brought to Abbots Bromley by William Paget, the ambassador to the Ottoman Empire.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] However, Paget's return from Turkey postdates the accounts of Plot and Degge which mention the horns.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Possibly Paget brought a set of horns back to Abbots Bromley when he returned from Turkey because horns were already used in the dance, and these later fell out of use as less practical than the original ones.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Wilkes also reports that the antlers were stored in Abbots Bromley town hall.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1820 Thomas Harwood was the first to report that they were stored in the church.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the late nineteenth century they were kept in the church tower; in 1927 they were moved and subsequently have been stored in the Hurst Chapel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] According to tradition, the horns must not leave the parish.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] A different set of horns, acquired in the 1950s, is used for performances outside Abbots Bromley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] One set of horns was apparently lost early in the 19th century; Marcia Rice reports a story that the Abbots Bromley dancers were bribed to bring the horns to Burton-upon-Trent, got drunk, and had the horns stolen.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1911, Cecil Sharp described the dance as being made up of two main figures.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the first, the dancers process around in a circle before turning and circling back.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In the second, the dancers face off in two rows, dancing together and apart before crossing over, turning around, and repeating the process to return to their original place.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] It is performed without any special footwork: Alford describes the dance as a "steady rhythmical plod".
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] There is no specific tune associated with the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1893, the vicar of Abbots Bromley recalled that there had previously been a special tune for the dance but that it had been lost.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1912, Sharp published a tune sent to him by a J.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Buckley which Buckley said he had collected in the 1850s from a fiddler from Abbots Bromley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] According to Andrew Bullen, "this is the tune most often associated with the horn dance and it is probably the oldest"; however, there is some dispute as to whether the tune did in fact accompany the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Cawte questions its authenticity, partly on stylistic grounds – "it is not in the character of tunes for other traditional dances" – and partly because the reputed source of the tune had never been the musician for the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Other tunes associated with the dance have been collected from William Adey, a dancer who in 1924 recalled a tune which he remembered being used in the 1870s and 1880s, and Edie Sammons, whose brother played for the dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] When Sharp collected the dance, "any country-dance air" was used; he saw it performed to *Yankee Doodle*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] More recently modern tunes have also been played.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Shortly after Sharp recorded the Abbots Bromley horn dance in *Sword Dances of Northern England*, versions of it began to be performed outside of the village by members of the English Folk Dance Society (now the English Folk Dance and Song Society or EFDSS).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The dance was brought to America in the 1920s, initially by Sharp's student May Gadd, and Frank Smith, the founder of the Berea College Country Dancers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Since 1947, a version of the dance has been performed by Thaxted Morris Men at the Thaxted meetings of the Morris Ring.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1951 they also performed the dance to celebrate the Festival of Britain.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 1966 the Abbots Bromley dancers performed at the Royal Albert Hall as part of EFDSS's annual festival; they also performed at Dancing England four times between 1979 and 2019.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] By 1993, 24 American morris sides listed the Abbots Bromley horn dance as one they performed in the annual *American Morris Newsletter* directory.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Ivon Hitchens' *Mural*, in the Kennedy Hall of Cecil Sharp House, the headquarters of the English Folk Dance and Song Society, depicts English folk-dances and traditions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The horn dancers shown on the right of the mural are probably based on those at Abbots Bromley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] Replicas of the horns, presented to EFDSS in 1930, are also kept at Cecil Sharp House.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] A series of pencil drawings by Dave Pearson, *In the Seven Woods*, also depict the Abbots Bromley dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] In 2019, Royal Mail issued a set of stamps depicting unusual British customs and festivals which included the Abbots Bromley horn dance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The dance was one of three traditional dances which inspired Hanna Tuulikki's "Deer Dancer".
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The artist and folk performer Lucy Wright's performance piece, "Non-Fertility Ritual", is a response to the interpretation of the Abbots Bromley dance as a fertility ritual.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley-horn-dance] The dance has been featured in exhibitions including *Mummers, Maypoles, and Milkmaids: A Journey Through the English Ritual Year* at the Horniman Museum in 2012, and *Making Michief: Folk Costume in Britain* at Compton Verney Art Gallery in 2023.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley was rated the best place to live in the Midlands by the *Sunday Times* in 2013 and again in 2016.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is a regular entrant and often winner of the Staffordshire Best Kept Village Competition which takes place across the county each year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Originally organised by the Community Council of Staffordshire there is a best-kept village award for a large and small village in each of the county's Districts and Boroughs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Whilst down the years the East Staffordshire district prize has been awarded to Abbots Bromley on a number of occasions the overall county title continues to elude.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In August 2017 the village won the double honour of winning both the best kept village and community council trophy award, a double not achieved for many years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In 2019 the competition was taken on by The Community Foundation for Staffordshire and Abbots Bromley won for the third consecutive year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Through the competition Abbots Bromley maintains a healthy rivalry with nearby Yoxall, also a regular winner in the East Staffordshire section.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is world-renowned for its annual Horn Dance, an ancient tradition which attracts visitors from far and wide.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village sits within the Postal Area of the nearby settlement of Rugeley which is the closest town to the village at 6.2 miles (10.0 km) from Abbots Bromley.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village and civil parish lie within the East Staffordshire District.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is 11.6 miles (18.7 km) north of the city of Lichfield and is 6.8 miles (10.9 km) south west of Uttoxeter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The nearest railway station is at Rugeley which is 5.8 miles (9.3 km) south west of the village.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Blithfield Reservoir is 1.8 miles (2.9 km) from the centre of the village.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Within the parish there are the natural features of Bagot's Wood and the largest remaining part of the Needwood Forest.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Phil Drabble's Goats Lodge nature reserve is also in the parish.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Chaserider hourly bus service 63 links the village to Uttoxeter, Rugeley, Hednesford and Cannock.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The first historical record of the village dates from 942, when the manor of "Bromleage" was given to Wulfsige the Black.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The will, dated 1002, of Wulfric Spot, Earl of Mercia, gave the village to the Abbey of Burton upon Trent.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] There is some evidence that the current settlement was a planned town – there is evidence of burgage plots, a grid pattern of streets and a wide market place.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbas Bromley is recorded in the *Domesday Book* of 1086–7 as *Brunlege*, when it was part of the land of St Mary of Burton.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In 1227, a weekly market was confirmed by Royal Charter at the site of the Buttercross (recorded in 1339, the present structure said by Pevsner to date from the 17th century), which survives to the present.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The current, triangular market place is now grassed over and serves as a village green and the focus for events on Horn Dance Day.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village remained affiliated to the Abbey until the Dissolution of the Monasteries in 1545.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Henry VIII gave *Bromley Abbatis* to Sir William Paget, Clerk of the Signet and Privy Councillor.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village was known as *Paget's Bromley* for several centuries, (distinguishing it from the part of the parish in the hands of the Bagot family, still known as *Bagot's Bromley*) but eventually the influence of the Paget family declined, and the name reverted to *Abbots Bromley*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Despite being an agricultural centre on account of its market and fairs, Abbots Bromley enjoyed some industrial success.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In the 16th century it was a major centre for glass manufacture.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In 1606 it gained a grammar school, now Richard Clarke First School.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Despite nineteenth century efforts to connect the village to the expanding railway network the North Staffordshire Railway received an act of parliament to build a branch line from Stowe-by-Chartley which was never taken advantage of.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley remained comparatively isolated and in decline, losing its market, fairs and economic status.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] By the 1950s the village faced economic decay and an ageing population.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] It was also comparatively late in receiving mains electricity and gas services.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] More recently it has become a dormitory settlement for surrounding urban areas such as the West Midlands conurbation and Derby.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] There has been some new development as well as the restoration of historic buildings, with a Millennium Hall perhaps the most noted recent example.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Nine parish councillors, elected every four years represent the community.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Every year the council elects a chair (currently Richard Love) and vice chair.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The parish council is supported by the parish clerk.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Meetings are usually held in the village hall at 19:00 on the last Wednesday of every month (except August and December due to holidays).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] One parish surgery is also held every other month on a Saturday morning in the Church House to enable parishioners to bring any local issues to the attention of a councillor so that it can be reported to the full parish council meeting.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Following the election of new parish councillors in May 2015 the council began the process of developing a neighbourhood plan, administered through a sub-group of the parish council.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley is part of the Bagots and Needwood Ward on East Staffordshire Borough Council and is currently represented by three Conservative borough councillors.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] At county level the village is part of the Needwood Forest Division, represented by Conservative Catherine Brown on Staffordshire County Council.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is part of the parliamentary constituency of Lichfield and is currently represented by Labour MP Dave Robertson.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is home to The Richard Clarke First School, run by the Uttoxeter Learning Trust for pupils aged 4–9.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The school was founded in 1606 via a bequest made by Richard Clarke a local man who achieved success in London in the trade of a dyer.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The school was originally known as 'Clarke's Grammar School'.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The current school is rated as good by OFSTED with outstanding features.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village is part of the three tier school system, now quite rare in England.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] From age 9-13 pupils go to Oldfields Hall Middle School in Uttoxeter and then from age 13-16 (or 18 if students opt to stay on in the sixth form) to Thomas Alleyne's High School also in Uttoxeter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village was also the home of one of the original Woodard Schools, and the first in the Woodard Group for girls Abbots Bromley School (formerly known as Abbots Bromley School for Girls and before that the School of S.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] In 2015 the school opened a new International College on the former St Mary's site.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The school closed in July 2019 and the site has been sold.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The site has been purchased by a property developer with plans to convert to residential properties.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The village has a large number of listed buildings, and its historic core has conservation area status, reflecting its pre-industrial townscape.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Of these, the half timbered Church House, The Goats Head Inn, which is claimed to be the original town hall, and the Schoolhouse (Richard Clarke's 1606 Grammar School) are some of the most noteworthy.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Market Cross (Buttercross) has been designated a scheduled Ancient Monument.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley is known for its annual Horn Dance, an English folk dance dating back to the Middle Ages.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The modern version of the dance involves reindeer antlers, a hobby horse, Maid Marian, and a Fool.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The dance takes place on Wakes Monday, the day following Wakes Sunday, which is the first Sunday after 4 September.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] It begins in the morning on the village green and passes to Blithfield Hall, returning to the village in the early afternoon with the dancers then making their way around the pubs and houses, eventually finishing with a service of Compline at the church.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley Cricket Club is an English amateur cricket club with a history of cricket in the village dating back to 1881.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The club ground is based on Mill Green Lane.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley CC have 2 Saturday senior XI teams that compete in the Derbyshire County Cricket League, a Sunday XI team, and a junior training section that play competitive cricket in the Burton & District Youth Cricket League.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley has a men's senior football team, Abbots Bromley FC, nicknamed 'The Stags'.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] They were reformed after over 10 years in 2010.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] They compete in division 2 of the Stafford & District league and play home games at the Abbots Bromley School grounds named 'The Lowers'.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Stags main sponsors are Gallery 3, The Room Network & Edwin Ferneyhough Vehicle Sales.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The president of the club is former Aston Villa and Stoke City footballer, Harry Burrows.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The club reached the Uttoxeter & District division 2/3 cup final in May 2012 but narrowly lost to Cheadle Town End on penalties in front of a crowd of 150+.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Stags also narrowly missed out on promotion to the Uttoxeter & District first division in 2012 after finishing third.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Stags were finally promoted to division 1 the following year and completed the double by winning the Subsidiary Cup after beating The Three Tuns FC in the final 4-1 at the Oldfield sports ground, Uttoxeter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The Subsidiary Cup win was repeated in 2017 when a 6-2 victory against Stone Town FC at Abbots Bromley School saw Will Ferneyhough score five goals.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The club remained in division 1 until 2018, a campaign that ended in relegation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The following season saw a second placed finish and promotion, narrowly losing out by a point to Doveridge FC as well as a 2-1 Division 2 League Cup final victory over Doveridge FC at Hillsfield, Rocester FC in front of over 200 spectators.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The club's committee voted to transfer to the Stafford & District League for the 2019-20 season and started out in the third tier (Division 2).
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley Netball Club is affiliated to England Netball with a Bronze CAPS status through the Sport England Clubmark scheme and consists of players of all ages from Abbots Bromley and surrounding areas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] The club uses the training and playing facilities at Abbots Bromley School, and field up to 3 squads in the Burton and District league.
[src:bog-snorkelling/abbots-bromley] Abbots Bromley Tennis Club was founded in 1913 and has two outdoor courts situated behind the Village Hall, off Bagot Street.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:bog-snorkelling/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bank-holiday] A **bank holiday** is a national public holiday in the United Kingdom and the Crown Dependencies, and a colloquial term for a public holiday in Ireland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bank-holiday] In the United Kingdom, the term is used to refer to all public holidays, be they set out in statute, declared by royal proclamation, or held by convention under common law.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bank-holiday] In Ireland, there are some bank holidays which are not public holidays.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bank-holiday] The term "bank holiday" refers to the fact that banking institutions typically close for business on such holidays, as they once did on certain saint's days.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC One and BBC Two are the flagship television channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Others include the youth channel BBC Three, cultural and documentary channel BBC Four, the British and international variations of the BBC News channel, parliamentary channel BBC Parliament, and two children's channels, CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Digital television is now entrenched in the UK, with analogue transmission completely phased out as of December 2012.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC One is a regionalised TV service which provides opt-outs throughout the day for local news and other local programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] These variations are more pronounced in the BBC "Nations", i.e.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, where the presentation is mostly carried out locally on BBC One and Two, and where programme schedules can vary considerably from that of the network.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Two variations exist in the Nations; however, English regions today rarely have the option to opt out as regional programming now exists only on BBC One.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2019, the Scottish variation of BBC Two ceased operation and was replaced with the networked version in favour of a new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Two was the first channel to be transmitted on 625 lines, in 1964.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It then carried a small-scale regular colour service from 1967.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] A new Scottish Gaelic television channel, BBC Alba, was launched in September 2008.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It is also the first multi-genre channel to come entirely from Scotland with almost all of its programmes made in Scotland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The service was initially available only via satellite but since June 2011 has been available to viewers in Scotland on Freeview and cable television.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC currently operates HD simulcasts of all its nationwide channels with the exception of BBC Parliament.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Until 26 March 2013, a separate channel called BBC HD was available, in place of BBC Two HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It launched on 15 May 2006, following a 12-month trial of the broadcasts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It became a proper channel in 2007, and screened HD programmes as simulcasts of the main network, or as repeats.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The corporation has been producing programmes in the format for many years, and stated that it hoped to produce 100% of new programmes in HDTV by 2010.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] On 3 November 2010, a high-definition simulcast of BBC One was launched, entitled BBC One HD, and BBC Two HD launched on 26 March 2013, replacing BBC HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Scotland's new television channel, BBC Scotland, launched in February 2019.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland, the BBC channels are available in a number of ways.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In these countries digital and cable operators carry a range of BBC channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since 1975 the BBC has also provided its TV programmes to the British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS), allowing members of UK military serving abroad to watch them on four dedicated TV channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] From 27 March 2013, BFBS will carry versions of BBC One and BBC Two, which will include children's programming from CBBC, as well as carrying programming from BBC Three on a new channel called BFBS Extra.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since 2008 all BBC channels are available to watch online through the BBC iPlayer service.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This online streaming ability came about following experiments with live streaming, involving streaming certain channels in the UK.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In February 2014, Director-General Tony Hall announced that the corporation needed to save £100 million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In March 2014, the BBC confirmed plans for BBC Three to become an internet-only channel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] An earlier ten months of listings are to be obtained from other sources.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] They identified about five million programmes, involving 8.5 million actors, presenters, writers and technical staff.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The Genome project was opened to public access on 15 October 2014, with corrections to OCR errors and changes to advertised schedules being crowdsourced.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has ten radio stations serving the whole of the UK, a further seven stations in the "national regions" (Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland), and 39 other local stations serving defined areas of England.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Of the ten national stations, five are major stations and are available on FM or AM as well as on DAB and online.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to these five stations, the BBC runs a further five stations that broadcast on DAB and online only.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] These stations supplement and expand on the big five stations, and were launched in 2002.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1Xtra sisters Radio 1, and broadcasts new Black music and urban tracks.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra sisters 5 Live and offers extra sport analysis, including broadcasting sports that previously were not covered.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 6 Music offers alternative music genres and is notable as a platform for new artists.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 7, later renamed BBC Radio 4 Extra, provides archive drama, comedy and children's programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The final station is the BBC Asian Network, providing music, talk and news to this section of the community.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This station evolved out of Local radio stations serving certain areas, and as such this station is available on medium wave frequency in some areas of the Midlands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As well as the national stations, the BBC also provides 40 BBC Local Radio stations in England and the Channel Islands, each named for and covering a particular city and its surrounding area (e.g.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Bristol), county or region (e.g.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Three Counties Radio), or geographical area (e.g.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Solent covering the central south coast).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] A further six stations broadcast in what the BBC terms "the national regions": Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] These are BBC Radio Wales (in English), BBC Radio Cymru (in Welsh), BBC Radio Scotland (in English), BBC Radio nan Gàidheal (in Scottish Gaelic), BBC Radio Ulster, and BBC Radio Foyle, the latter being an opt-out station from Radio Ulster for the north-west of Northern Ireland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC's UK national channels are also broadcast in the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man (although these Crown Dependencies are outside the UK), and in the former there are two local stations – BBC Radio Guernsey and BBC Radio Jersey.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] There is no BBC local radio station, however, in the Isle of Man, partly because the island has long been served by the popular independent commercial station, Manx Radio, which predates the existence of BBC Local Radio.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC services in the dependencies are financed from television licence fees which are set at the same level as those payable in the UK, although collected locally.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This is the subject of some controversy in the Isle of Man since, as well as having no BBC Local Radio service, the island also lacks a local television news service analogous to that provided by BBC Channel Islands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It is broadcast worldwide on shortwave radio, DAB and online and has an estimated weekly audience of 192 million, and its websites have an audience of 38 million people per week.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since 2005, it is also available on DAB in the UK, a step not taken before, due to the way it is funded.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Following the Government's spending review in 2011, the service was funded for the first time through the Licence fee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In recent years, some services of the World Service have been reduced: the Thai service ended in 2006, as did the Eastern European languages.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Resources were diverted instead into the new BBC News Arabic.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Historically the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster based in the UK mainland until 1967, when University Radio York, then under the name *Radio York*, was launched as the first, and now oldest, legal independent radio station in the country.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] However, the BBC did not enjoy a complete monopoly before this, as several Continental stations, such as Radio Luxembourg, had broadcast programmes in English to Britain since the 1930s and the Isle of Man-based Manx Radio began in 1964.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Today, despite the advent of commercial broadcasting, BBC radio stations remain among the most listened-to in the country.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Radio 2 has the largest audience share (up to 16.8% in 2011–12) and Radios 1 and 4 ranked second and third in terms of weekly reach.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC programming is also available to other services and in other countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since 1943, the BBC has provided radio programming to the British Forces Broadcasting Service, which broadcasts in countries where British troops are stationed.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1 is also carried in Canada on SiriusXM (online streaming only).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC is a patron of the Radio Academy, a registered UK charity that promotes excellence in broadcasting.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC News is the largest broadcast news gathering operation in the world, providing services to BBC domestic radio as well as television networks such as the BBC News, BBC Parliament and BBC News International.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to this, news stories are available on the BBC Red Button service and BBC News Online.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to this, the BBC has been developing new ways to access BBC News and as a result, has launched the service on BBC Mobile, making it accessible to mobile phones and PDAs, as well as developing alerts by email, on digital television, and on computers through a desktop alert.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Ratings figures suggest that during major incidents such as the 7 July 2005 London bombings or royal events, the UK audience overwhelmingly turns to the BBC's coverage as opposed to its commercial rivals.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] On 7 July 2005, the day there were a series of coordinated bomb blasts on London's public transport system, the BBC Online website recorded an all time bandwidth peak of 11 Gb/s at 12.00 on 7 July.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC News received some 1 billion total hits on the day of the event (including all images, text, and HTML), serving some 5.5 terabytes of data.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] At peak times during the day, there were 40,000-page requests per second for the BBC News website.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The previous day's announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics being awarded to London caused a peak of about 5 Gbit/s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The previous all-time high at BBC Online was caused by the announcement of the Michael Jackson verdict, which used 7.2 Gbit/s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC's online presence includes a comprehensive news website and archive.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC's first official online service was the BBC Networking Club, which was launched on 11 May 1994.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The service was subsequently relaunched as BBC Online in 1997, before being renamed BBCi, then bbc.co.uk, before it was rebranded back as BBC Online.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The website is funded by the Licence fee, but uses GeoIP technology, allowing advertisements to be carried on the site when viewed outside of the UK.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC claims the site to be "Europe's most popular content-based site" and states that 13.2 million people in the UK visit the site's more than two million pages each day.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The centre of the website is the Homepage, which features a modular layout.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Users can choose which modules, and which information, is displayed on their homepage, allowing the user to customise it.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This system was first launched in December 2007, becoming permanent in February 2008, and has undergone a few aesthetical changes since then.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The home page then has links to other micro-sites, such as BBC News Online, Sport, Weather, TV, and Radio.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As part of the site, every programme on BBC Television or Radio is given its own page, with bigger programmes getting their own micro-site, and as a result it is often common for viewers and listeners to be told URLs for the programme website.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allowed legal downloads of selected archive material via the internet.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has often included learning as part of its online service, running services such as BBC Jam, Learning Zone Class Clips and also runs services such as BBC WebWise and First Click which are designed to teach people how to use the internet.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Jam was a free online service, delivered through broadband and narrowband connections, providing high-quality interactive resources designed to stimulate learning at home and at school.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Initial content was made available in January 2006; however, BBC Jam was suspended on 20 March 2007 due to allegations made to the European Commission that it was damaging the interests of the commercial sector of the industry.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In recent years some major on-line companies and politicians have complained that BBC Online receives too much funding from the television licence, meaning that other websites are unable to compete with the vast amount of advertising-free on-line content available on BBC Online.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Some have proposed that the amount of licence fee money spent on BBC Online should be reduced—either being replaced with funding from advertisements or subscriptions, or a reduction in the amount of content available on the site.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In response to this the BBC carried out an investigation, and has now set in motion a plan to change the way it provides its online services.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Online will now attempt to fill in gaps in the market, and will guide users to other websites for currently existing market provision.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] (For example, instead of providing local events information and timetables, users will be guided to outside websites already providing that information.) Part of this plan included the BBC closing some of its websites, and rediverting money to redevelop other parts.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network, as part of Mark Thompson's plans to make "a smaller, fitter BBC for the digital age".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Red Button is the brand name for the BBC's interactive television services, which are available through Freeview (digital terrestrial), as well as Freesat, Sky UK (satellite), and Virgin Media (cable).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Unlike Ceefax, the service's analogue counterpart, BBC Red Button is able to display full-colour graphics, photographs, and video, as well as programmes and can be accessed from any BBC channel.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The service carries News, Weather and Sport 24 hours a day, but also provides extra features related to programmes specific at that time.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Examples include viewers to play along at home to gameshows, to give, voice and vote on opinions to issues, as used alongside programmes such as *Question Time*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] At some points in the year, when multiple sporting events occur, some coverage of less mainstream sports or games are frequently placed on the Red Button for viewers to watch.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Frequently, other features are added unrelated to programmes being broadcast at that time, such as the broadcast of the *Doctor Who* animated episode *Dreamland* in November 2009.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It also buys a selected number of broadcasts from the Ulster Orchestra in Belfast and the BBC Big Band.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC Proms have been produced by the BBC every year since 1927, stepping in to fund the popular eight-week summer classical music festival when music publishers Chappell and Co withdrew their support.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 1930, the newly formed BBC Symphony Orchestra gave all 49 Proms, and have performed at every Last Night of the Proms since then.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The Proms have been held at the Royal Albert Hall since 1941, and the BBC's orchestras and choirs are the backbone of the festival, giving about 40% to 50% of all performances each season.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Many famous musicians of every genre have played at the BBC, such as The Beatles (*Live at the BBC* is one of their many albums).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC is also responsible for the broadcast of Glastonbury Festival, Reading and Leeds Festivals and United Kingdom coverage of the Eurovision Song Contest, a show with which the broadcaster has been associated for over 60 years.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates the division of BBC Audiobooks sometimes found in association with Chivers Audiobooks.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC operates other ventures as well as its broadcasting arm.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to broadcasting output on television and radio, some programmes are also displayed on the BBC Big Screens in several central-city locations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC and the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office also jointly run BBC Monitoring, which monitors radio, television, the press and the internet worldwide.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The National Museum of Computing at Bletchley Park uses BBC Micros as part of a scheme to educate school children about computer programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 1951, in conjunction with Oxford University Press, the BBC published *The BBC Hymn Book*, intended to be used by radio listeners to follow hymns being broadcast.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The book was published both with and without music, the music edition being entitled *The BBC Hymn Book with Music*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC provided the world's first teletext service called Ceefax (near-homophonous with "See Facts") from 23 September 1974 until 23 October 2012 on the BBC1 analogue channel, then later on BBC2.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It showed informational pages, such as news, sport, and the weather.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] From New Year's Eve, 1974, ITV's Oracle tried to compete with Ceefax.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] During its lifetime, Ceefax attracted millions of viewers, right up until 2012, prior to the digital switchover in the United Kingdom.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Since then, the BBC's Red Button Service has provided a digital information system that replaced Ceefax.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2016 the BBC, in partnership with fellow UK broadcasters ITV and Channel 4 (the latter later withdrew from the project), set up 'project kangaroo' to develop an international online streaming service to rival services such as Netflix and Hulu.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] During the development stages 'Britflix' was touted as a potential name.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] However, the service eventually launched as BritBox in March 2017.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The online platform shows a catalogue of classic BBC and ITV shows, as well as making a number of programmes available shortly after their UK broadcast.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As of 2021, BritBox is available in the UK, the US, Canada, Australia, and, more recently, South Africa, with the potential availability for new markets in the future.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Studios is the wholly owned commercial subsidiary of the BBC, responsible for the commercial exploitation of BBC programmes and other properties, including a number of television stations throughout the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It was formed in 2018 after the merger of the BBC's commercial production arm and the BBC's commercial international distribution arm, BBC Worldwide, with the latter formed in 1995 following the restructuring of its predecessor, BBC Enterprises.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Prior to this, the selling of BBC television programmes was at first handled in 1958 with the establishment of a business manager post.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This expanded until the establishment of the Television Promotions (renamed Television Enterprises) department in 1960 under a general manager.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The company owns and administers a number of commercial stations around the world operating in a number of territories and on a number of different platforms.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] These include BBC UKTV for the Australasia region, and formerly BBC America (now fully owned by AMC Networks).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The company airs two channels aimed at children, an international CBeebies channel and BBC Kids, a joint venture with Knowledge Network Corporation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The company also runs BBC Earth, which distributes the BBC's natural history content to countries outside the UK, and BBC Lifestyle, broadcasting programmes based on themes of Food, Style and Wellbeing.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to this, BBC Studios ran an international version of the channel BBC HD.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also distributes the 24-hour international news channel BBC News.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The station is separate from BBC Studios to maintain the station's neutral point of view, but is distributed by BBC Studios.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The channel itself is the oldest surviving entity of its kind, and has 50 foreign news bureaus and correspondents in nearly all countries in the world.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] As officially surveyed, it is available to more than 294 million households, significantly more than CNN's estimated 200 million.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to these international channels, BBC Studios also owns the UKTV network of seven channels.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] These channels contain BBC archive programming to be rebroadcast on their respective channels: Alibi, crime dramas; Dave (slogan: "The Home of Witty Banter"); Drama, drama, launched in 2013; Eden, nature; Gold, comedy; W, Entertainment; and Yesterday, history programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to these channels, many BBC programmes are sold via BBC Studios to foreign television stations with comedy, documentaries, crime dramas (such as *Luther* and *Peaky Blinders*) and historical drama productions being the most popular.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC's most successful reality television show format, *Strictly Come Dancing*—under the title *Dancing with the Stars*—has been exported to 60 other countries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Shows commissioned and distributed by the BBC include the *Wallace & Gromit* animated comedy short films *The Wrong Trousers* and *A Close Shave*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC television news also appears nightly on many PBS stations in the US, as do reruns of BBC programmes such as *EastEnders*, and in New Zealand on TVNZ 1.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In addition to programming, BBC Studios produces material to accompany programmes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The company maintained the publishing arm of the BBC, BBC Magazines, which published the *Radio Times*; first published by the BBC on 28 September 1923, it is the world's first broadcast listings magazine.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] *Radio Times* covers all British television and radio programming schedules, and the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11,220,666 copies, which the *Guinness World Records* certified as the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Other magazines that support BBC programming include *BBC Top Gear*, *BBC Good Food*, *BBC Sky at Night*, *BBC History*, *BBC Wildlife* and *BBC Music*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Magazines was sold to Exponent Private Equity in 2011, which merged it with Origin Publishing (previously owned by BBC Worldwide between 2004 and 2006) to form Immediate Media Company.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also publishes books, to accompany programmes such as *Sherlock* and *Doctor Who* under the BBC Books brand, a publishing imprint majority owned by Random House.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Archive programming and classical music recordings are sold under the brand BBC Legends.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Until the development, popularisation, and domination of television, radio was the broadcast medium upon which people in the United Kingdom relied.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It "reached into every home in the land, and simultaneously united the nation, an important factor during the Second World War".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC introduced the world's first "high-definition" 405-line television service in 1936.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It suspended its television service during the Second World War and until 1946, but remained the only television broadcaster in the UK until 1955, when Independent Television (ITV) began operating.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] This heralded the transformation of television into a popular and dominant medium.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Nevertheless, "throughout the 1950s radio still remained the dominant source of broadcast comedy".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Further, the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster until 1968 (when University Radio York obtained its first licence).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Despite the advent of commercial television and radio, with competition from ITV, Channel 4 and Sky, the BBC has remained one of the main elements in British popular culture through its obligation to produce TV and radio programmes for mass audiences.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] However, the arrival of BBC2 allowed the BBC also to make programmes for minority interests in drama, documentaries, current affairs, entertainment, and sport.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Described as television's first "watercooler moment" by *The Telegraph*, the BBC's 1954 adaptation of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* made a dramatic impact on a fledgling television audience who were horrified by the graphic depiction of a totalitarian regime controlling the population.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Making his BBC debut in 1949, Benny Hill with *The Benny Hill Show* became the first British comedian to become famous via television.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Popular comedy duos on the BBC include Morecambe and Wise (whose show debuted in 1968) and The Two Ronnies (debuting in 1971).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Black comedy sitcom *Blackadder*, starring Rowan Atkinson as the title character, ran for four series between 1983 and 1989.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The British Academy Film Awards (BAFTAs) was first broadcast on the BBC in 1956, with Vivien Leigh as the host.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The television equivalent, the British Academy Television Awards, has been screened exclusively on the BBC since a 2007 awards ceremony that included wins for Jim Broadbent (Best actor) and Ricky Gervais (Best comedy performance).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The term "BBC English" was used as an alternative name for Received Pronunciation, and the *English Pronouncing Dictionary* uses the term "BBC Pronunciation" to label its recommendations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] However, the BBC itself now makes more use of regional accents to reflect the diversity of the UK, while continuing to expect clarity and fluency of its presenters.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] From its "starchy" beginnings, the BBC has also become more inclusive, and now attempts to accommodate the interests of all strata of society and all minorities, because they all pay the licence fee.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Older domestic UK audiences often refer to the BBC as "the Beeb", a nickname coined by Peter Sellers during a 1972 reunion of the 1950s BBC radio comedy *The Goon Show*, when he referred to the "Beeb Beeb Ceeb".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It was then shortened and popularised by radio DJ Kenny Everett.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] David Bowie's recording sessions at the BBC were released as *Bowie at the Beeb*, while Queen's BBC recording sessions were released as *At the Beeb*.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The term "Auntie" for the BBC is often credited to radio disc-jockey Jack Jackson.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] To celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the BBC the song "Auntie" was released in 1972.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It also featured in the title of the BBC's blooper show, *Auntie's Bloomers*, which was presented by Terry Wogan from 1991 to 2001.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The two nicknames have also been used together as "Auntie Beeb".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Throughout its existence the BBC has faced numerous accusations regarding many topics: the Iraq war, the Gaza war, politics, ethics and religion, as well as funding and staffing.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It also has been involved in numerous controversies because of its coverage of specific news stories and programming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has been accused repeatedly of anti-Israel bias, and to a greater extent anti-Israel Defense Force bias.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has long faced accusations of liberal and left-wing bias.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Accusations of a bias against the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party were often made against the BBC by members of that government, with Margaret Thatcher herself considering the broadcaster's news coverage to be biased and irresponsible.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2011, Peter Sissons, a main news presenter at the BBC from 1989 to 2009, said that "at the core of the BBC, in its very DNA, is a way of thinking that is firmly of the Left".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Another BBC presenter, Andrew Marr, commented that "the BBC is not impartial or neutral.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It has a liberal bias, not so much a party-political bias.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] It is better expressed as a cultural liberal bias." Former BBC director Roger Mosey classified it as "liberal defensive".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In 2022, the BBC chairman, Richard Sharp, said that the BBC "does have a liberal bias" and that the institution is "fighting against it".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In November 2025, allegations by *The Daily Telegraph* that the BBC had deceptively spliced a Donald Trump speech preceding the January 6 United States Capitol attack in a documentary led to several BBC executives resigning, including the head of the BBC.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Writing for *The Guardian* in 2018, the left-wing columnist Owen Jones stated "the truth is the BBC is stacked full of rightwingers," and cited as an example of bias its employment of "ultra-Thatcherite" Andrew Neil as a politics presenter.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] In November 2025, LibDem leader Ed Davey called for Gibb's removal from the BBC board because of Gibb's alleged role in the 2025 BBC editorial bias controversy.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] A 2018 opinion poll by BMG Research found that 40% of the British public thought that the BBC was politically partisan, with a nearly even split between those who believed it leaned to the left or right.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Additionally oft-cited are its policy of "balancing" appearances by transgender people with activists from gender-critical groups, its manual of style which requires any allegations of transphobia to be challenged by the news presenter, and its policy against using the term "cisgender".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] The BBC has also been accused by gender-critical groups and BBC staff of having a pro-trans bias, primarily for "failing to make it clear that transgender women are biological males".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Such accusations have alleged that the BBC's LGBT desk has been "captured by a small group of people" intent on promoting a pro-trans agenda.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bbc-p02] Shortly thereafter, the BBC began running articles referring to trans women as "biological males who identify as women".
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] The women's world record stands at 1 minute 22.56 seconds by Kirsty Johnson in 2014.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] The men's world record was set by Neil Rutter in 2018, with a time of 1 min 18.81 seconds.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] Both were set at the Waen Rhydd bog, Llanwrtyd Wells in Wales.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] The **World Bog Snorkelling Championship**, first held in 1988, takes place every August Bank Holiday in the dense Waen Rhydd peat bog, near Llanwrtyd Wells in mid Wales.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] Competitors travel from as far afield as Australia, Belgium, Canada, China, England, Finland, Germany, Ireland, New Zealand, Poland, Russia, South Africa, South Korea, Wales and the US.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] Other bog snorkelling events take place, particularly in Wales, but also in Australia, Ireland, and Sweden.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] These include the Bog Snorkelling Triathlon, which consists of a 120 yards (110 metres) snorkel, a 19 miles (31 kilometres) bike ride and a 7+1⁄2 miles (12.1 km) run.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] Proceeds from the World Championship go to a local charity each year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] Past recipients include the Cystic Fibrosis Trust (2005) and the Motor Neurone Association (2006).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog-snorkelling] The 2006 charity was chosen in memory of the Green Events treasurer, Ron Skilton, who died in December 2005.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A **bog** or **bogland** is a wetland that accumulates peat as a deposit of dead plant materials – often mosses, typically sphagnum moss.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] It is one of the four main types of wetlands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Other names for bogs include mire, mosses, quagmire, and muskeg; alkaline mires are called fens.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A bayhead is another type of bog found in the forest of the Gulf Coast states in the United States.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] They are often covered in heath or heather shrubs rooted in the sphagnum moss and peat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The gradual accumulation of decayed plant material in a bog functions as a carbon sink.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs occur where the water at the ground surface is acidic and low in nutrients.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A bog usually is found at a freshwater soft spongy ground that is made up of decayed plant matter which is known as peat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] They are generally found in cooler northern climates and are formed in poorly draining lake basins.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In contrast to fens, they derive most of their water from precipitation rather than mineral-rich ground or surface water.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Water flowing out of bogs has a characteristic brown colour, which comes from dissolved peat tannins.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In general, the low fertility and cool climate result in relatively slow plant growth, but decay is even slower due to low oxygen levels in saturated bog soils.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Large areas of the landscape can be covered many meters deep in peat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs have distinctive assemblages of animal, fungal, and plant species, and are of high importance for biodiversity, particularly in landscapes that are otherwise settled and farmed.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs are widely distributed in cold, temperate climes, mostly in boreal ecosystems in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The world's largest wetland is the peat bogs of the Western Siberian Lowlands in Russia, which cover more than a million square kilometres.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Large peat bogs also occur in North America, particularly the Hudson Bay Lowland and the Mackenzie River Basin.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] They are less common in the Southern Hemisphere, with the largest being the Magellanic moorland, comprising some 44,000 square kilometres (17,000 sq mi) in southern South America.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Sphagnum bogs were widespread in northern Europe but have often been cleared and drained for agriculture.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Swindles in 2019 showed that peatlands across Europe have undergone rapid drying in recent centuries owing to human impacts including drainage, peat cutting and burning.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A 2014 expedition leaving from Itanga village, Republic of the Congo, discovered a peat bog "as big as England" which stretches into neighboring Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Ireland's geography was once covered in boglands prior to mass deforestation during the 1800s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Like all wetlands, it is difficult to rigidly define bogs for a number of reasons, including variations between bogs, the in-between nature of wetlands as an intermediate between terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems, and varying definitions between wetland classification systems.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The wetland receives most of its water and nutrients from precipitation (ombrotrophic) rather than surface or groundwater (minerotrophic).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The wetland is nutrient-poor (oligotrophic).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The wetland is strongly acidic (bogs near coastal areas may be less acidic due to sea spray).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Because all bogs have peat, they are a type of peatland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] As a peat-producing ecosystem, they are also classified as mires, along with fens.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs differ from fens, in that fens receive water and nutrients from mineral-rich surface or groundwater, while bogs receive water and nutrients from precipitation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Because fens are supplied with mineral-rich water, they tend to range from slightly acidic to slightly basic, while bogs are always acidic because precipitation lacks the dissolved minerals (e.g. calcium, magnesium, carbonate) that act to buffer the natural acidity of atmospheric carbon dioxide.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Geography and geology both impact the hydrology: as groundwater mineral content reflects the bedrock geology, there can be great deal of variability in some common ions (e.g. manganese, iron) while proximity to coastal areas is associated with higher sulfate and sodium concentrations.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] There are many highly specialized animals, fungi, and plants associated with bog habitat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Most are capable of tolerating the combination of low nutrient levels and waterlogging.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Sphagnum is generally abundant, along with ericaceous shrubs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The shrubs are often evergreen, which may assist in conservation of nutrients.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In drier locations, evergreen trees can occur, in which case the bog blends into the surrounding expanses of boreal evergreen forest.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Sedges are one of the more common herbaceous species.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Carnivorous plants such as sundews (*Drosera*) and pitcher plants (for example *Sarracenia purpurea*) have adapted to the low-nutrient conditions by using invertebrates as a nutrient source.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Orchids have adapted to these conditions through the use of mycorrhizal fungi to extract nutrients.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Some shrubs such as *Myrica gale* (bog myrtle) have root nodules in which nitrogen fixation occurs, thereby providing another supplemental source of nitrogen.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs are recognized as a significant/specific habitat type by a number of governmental and conservation agencies.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] They can provide habitat for mammals, such as caribou, moose, and beavers, as well as for species of nesting shorebirds, such as Siberian cranes and yellowlegs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs contain species of vulnerable reptilians such as the bog turtle.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs even have distinctive insects; English bogs give a home to a yellow fly called the hairy canary fly (*Phaonia jaroschewskii*), and bogs in North America are habitat for a butterfly called the bog copper (*Lycaena epixanthe*).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In Ireland, the viviparous lizard, the only known reptile in the country, dwells in bogland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The United Kingdom in its Biodiversity Action Plan establishes bog habitats as a priority for conservation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Russia has a large reserve system in the West Siberian Lowland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The highest protected status occurs in Zapovedniks (IUCN category IV); Gydansky and Yugansky are two prominent examples.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs are fragile ecosystems, and have been deteriorating quickly, as archaeologists and scientists have been recently finding.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bone material found in bogs has had accelerated deterioration from first analyses in the 1940s.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] This has been found to be from fluctuations in ground water and increase in acidity in lower areas of bogs that is affecting the rich organic material.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Many of these areas have been permeated to the lowest levels with oxygen, which dries and cracks layers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] There have been some temporary solutions to try to fix these issues, such as adding soil to the tops of threatened areas; they do not work in the long-term.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Extreme weather like dry summers are likely the cause, as they lower precipitation and the groundwater table.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] It is speculated that these issues will only increase with a rise in global temperature and climate change.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Since bogs take thousands of years to form and create the rich peat that is used as a resource, once they are gone they are extremely hard to recover.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Arctic and sub-Arctic circles where many bogs are warming at 0.6 °C per decade, an amount twice as large as the global average.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Because bogs and other peatlands are carbon sinks, they are releasing large amounts of greenhouse gases as they warm up.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These changes have resulted in a severe decline of biodiversity and species populations of peatlands throughout Northern Europe.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bog habitats may develop in various situations, depending on the climate and topography.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs may be classified on their topography, proximity to water, method of recharge, and nutrient accumulation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These develop in gently sloping valleys or hollows.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A layer of peat fills the deepest part of the valley, and a stream may run through the surface of the bog.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Valley bogs may develop in relatively dry and warm climates, but because they rely on ground or surface water, they only occur on acidic substrates.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These develop from a lake or flat marshy area, over either non-acidic or acidic substrates.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Over centuries there is a progression from open lake, to a marsh, to a fen (or, on acidic substrates, valley bog), to a carr, as silt or peat accumulates within the lake.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Eventually, peat builds up to a level where the land surface is too flat for ground or surface water to reach the center of the wetland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] This part, therefore, becomes wholly rain-fed (ombrotrophic), and the resulting acidic conditions allow the development of bog (even if the substrate is non-acidic).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The bog continues to form peat, and over time a shallow dome of bog peat develops into a raised bog.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The dome is typically a few meters high in the center and is often surrounded by strips of fen or other wetland vegetation at the edges or along streamsides where groundwater can percolate into the wetland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In cool climates with consistently high rainfall (on more than c.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] 235 days a year), the ground surface may remain waterlogged for much of the time, providing conditions for the development of bog vegetation.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In these circumstances, bog develops as a layer "blanketing" much of the land, including hilltops and slopes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Although a blanket bog is more common on acidic substrates, under some conditions it may also develop on neutral or even alkaline ones, if abundant acidic rainwater predominates over the groundwater.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A blanket bog can occur in drier or warmer climates, because under those conditions hilltops and sloping ground dry out too often for peat to form – in intermediate climates a blanket bog may be limited to areas which are shaded from direct sunshine.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In periglacial climates a patterned form of blanket bog may occur, known as a string bog.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In Europe, these mostly very thin peat layers without significant surface structures are distributed over the hills and valleys of Ireland, Scotland, England, and Norway.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In North America, blanket bogs occur predominantly in Canada east of Hudson Bay.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These bogs are often still under the influence of mineral soil water (groundwater).
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Blanket bogs do not occur north of the 65th latitude in the northern hemisphere.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A *quaking bog*, *schwingmoor*, or *swingmoor* is a form of floating bog occurring in wetter parts of valley bogs and raised bogs and sometimes around the edges of acidic lakes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The bog vegetation, mostly sphagnum moss anchored by sedges (such as *Carex lasiocarpa*), forms a floating mat approximately half a meter thick on the surface of water or above very wet peat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] White spruce (*Picea glauca*) may grow in this bog regime.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Walking on the surface causes it to move – larger movements may cause visible ripples on the surface, or they may even make trees sway.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The bog mat may eventually spread across the water surface to cover bays or even entire small lakes.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bogs at the edges of lakes may become detached and form floating islands.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] A cataract bog is a rare ecological community formed where a permanent stream flows over a granite outcropping.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The sheeting of water keeps the edges of the rock wet without eroding the soil, but in this precarious location, no tree or large shrub can maintain a roothold.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The result is a narrow, permanently wet habitat.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] After drying, peat is used as a fuel, and it has been used that way for centuries.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] More than 20% of home heat in Ireland comes from peat, and it is also used for fuel in Finland, Scotland, Germany, and Russia.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Russia is the leading exporter of peat for fuel, at more than 90 million metric tons per year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Ireland's *Bord na Móna* ("peat board") was one of the first companies to mechanically harvest peat, which is being phased out.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The other major use of dried peat is as a soil amendment (sold as *moss peat* or *sphagnum peat*) to increase the soil's capacity to retain moisture and enrich the soil.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Some distilleries, notably in the Islay whisky-producing region, use the smoke from peat fires to dry the barley used in making Scotch whisky.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Once the peat has been extracted it can be difficult to restore the wetland, since peat accumulation is a slow process.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] More than 90% of the bogs in England have been damaged or destroyed.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] In 2011 plans for the elimination of peat in gardening products were announced by the UK government.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The peat in bogs is an important place for the storage of carbon.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] If the peat decays, carbon dioxide would be released to the atmosphere, contributing to global warming.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Undisturbed, bogs function as a carbon sink.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] As one example, the peatlands of the former Soviet Union were calculated to be removing 52 Tg of carbon per year from the atmosphere.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Therefore, the rewetting of drained peatlands may be one of the most cost-effective ways to mitigate climate change.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Peat bogs are also important in storing fresh water, particularly in the headwaters of large rivers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Even the enormous Yangtze River arises in the Ruoergai peatland near its headwaters in Tibet.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Blueberries, cranberries, cloudberries, huckleberries, and lingonberries are harvested from the wild in bogs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Bog oak, wood that has been partially preserved by bogs, has been used in the manufacture of furniture.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Sphagnum bogs are also used for outdoor recreation, with activities including ecotourism and hunting.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] For example, many popular canoe routes in northern Canada include areas of peatland.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Some other activities, such as all-terrain vehicle use, are especially damaging to bogs.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The anaerobic environment and presence of tannic acids within bogs can result in the remarkable preservation of organic material.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Finds of such material have been made in Slovenia, Denmark, Germany, Ireland, Russia, and the United Kingdom.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Some bogs have preserved bog-wood, such as ancient oak logs useful in dendrochronology.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] They have yielded extremely well-preserved bog bodies, with hair, organs, and skin intact, buried there thousands of years ago after apparent Germanic and Celtic human sacrifice.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Excellent examples of such human specimens include the Haraldskær Woman and Tollund Man in Denmark, and Lindow man found at Lindow Common in England.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] The Tollund Man was so well preserved that when the body was discovered in 1950, the discoverers thought it was a recent murder victim and researchers were even able to tell the last meal that the Tollund Man ate before he died: porridge and fish.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] This process happens because of the low oxygen levels of bogs in combination with the high acidity.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These anaerobic conditions lead to some of the best-preserved mummies and offer much archeological insight into society as far as 8,000 years back.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] Céide Fields in County Mayo in Ireland, a 5,000-year-old neolithic farming landscape has been found preserved under a blanket bog, complete with field walls and hut sites.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] One ancient artifact found in various bogs is bog butter, large masses of fat, usually in wooden containers.
[src:bog-snorkelling/bog] These are thought to have been food stores of both butter and tallow.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] The **'Obby 'Oss festival** (/ˈɒbi ˈɒs/) is a folk custom that takes place each 1st of May in Padstow, a coastal town in North Cornwall.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] It involves two separate processions making their way around the town, each containing an eponymous hobby horse known as the 'Obby 'Oss.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] The festival starts at midnight on the 30th of April when townspeople gather outside the Golden Lion Inn to sing the "Night Song".
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] By morning, the town has been dressed with greenery and flowers placed around the maypole.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] The excitement begins with the appearance of one of the 'Obby 'Osses.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Male dancers cavort through the town dressed as one of two 'Obby 'Osses, the "Old" and the "Blue Ribbon" or "Methodist" 'Obby 'Osses; as the name suggests, they are stylised depictions of horses.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Prodded on by assistants known as "Teasers", each wears a mask and black frame-hung cape under which they try to catch young maidens as they pass through the town.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Throughout the day, the two parades, led by the "MC" (Master of Ceremonies) in his top hat and decorated stick, followed by a band of accordions and drums, then the 'Oss and the Teaser, with a host of people, the "Mayers" – all singing the "Morning Song" – pass along the streets of the town.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Finally, late in the evening, the two 'osses meet, at the maypole, before returning to their respective stables where the crowd sings of the 'Obby 'Oss death, until its resurrection the following May Eve.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] During the twentieth century the existence of the festival was described by a number of folklorists who brought greater attention to it.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] This helped to make the event a popular tourist attraction and establish it as one of the most famous folk customs in Britain.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] The festival takes place on May Day every year.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] It entails two separate processions that make their way around Padstow on circuits that take twelve hours to traverse.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Each procession represents a different half of the town's community.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Only those whose families have lived in Padstow for at least two generations are permitted to take part in the processions.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] Each procession includes an 'Obby 'Oss, a hobby horse consisting of an oval frame covered in black oilskin, which has a small horse's head in the front with a snapping jaw.
[src:bog-snorkelling/obby-oss-festival] This is led by an individual known as the Teaser, who is dressed in white and carries a painted club.
